03904nam a22004575i 9780226169095DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20142014ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226169095  a(DE-B1597)523579  a(OCoLC)891081459  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 7aHIS0000002bisacsh1 aNirenberg, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNeighboring Faiths :bChristianity, Islam, and Judaism in the Middle Ages and Today /cDavid Nirenberg. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. Neighboring Faiths -- t1.Christendom and Islam -- t2. Love between Muslim and Jew -- t3. Deviant Politics and Jewish Love: Alfonso VIII and the Jewess of Toledo -- t4 Massacre or Miracle? Valencia, 1391 -- t5. Conversion, Sex, and Segregation -- t6. Figures of Thought and Figures of Flesh -- t7. Mass Conversion and Genealogical Mentalities -- t8. Was There Race before Modernity? The Example of “Jewish” Blood in Late Medieval Spain -- t9. Islam and the West: Two Dialectical Fantasies -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography of Works Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aChristianity, Judaism, and Islam are usually treated as autonomous religions, but in fact across the long course of their histories the three religions have developed in interaction with one another. In Neighboring Faiths, David Nirenberg examines how Muslims, Christians, and Jews lived with and thought about each other during the Middle Ages and what the medieval past can tell us about how they do so today. There have been countless scripture-based studies of the three “religions of the book,” but Nirenberg goes beyond those to pay close attention to how the three religious neighbors loved, tolerated, massacred, and expelled each other—all in the name of God—in periods and places both long ago and far away. Nirenberg argues that the three religions need to be studied in terms of how each affected the development of the others over time, their proximity of religious and philosophical thought as well as their overlapping geographies, and how the three “neighbors” define—and continue to define—themselves and their place in terms of one another. From dangerous attractions leading to interfaith marriage; to interreligious conflicts leading to segregation, violence, and sometimes extermination; to strategies for bridging the interfaith gap through language, vocabulary, and poetry, Nirenberg aims to understand the intertwined past of the three faiths as a way for their heirs to produce the future—together.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022616893740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226169095423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226169095/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles